Format of tutorial materials

“Code chunks” appear in grey boxes throughout the tutorials. These represent verbatim the code that you will use in R, either in the console or in a script.

# Anything behind a pound sign is a comment
# Use these to leave notes to your future self or others
##########################################################
### or to break up sections of code

# Comments can exist on their own line
1 + 1 # or at the end of a line of code
## [1] 2

Output is printed under the code chunk. As we go along, compare your output to that shown in these materials.

RStudio

The console is where you will type (or paste) commands.

You open scripts in the Source Window.

  • File > New File > R Script (or click the button with the green + sign in the top left corner)
  • An R script is like a Stata do file.
  • You can save and re-run commands straight from the script.

Running commands in the console

Type directly into the console. At the end of each line, press Enter.

14 + 9
## [1] 23
x = 9
14 + x
## [1] 23
y = c(9, -9)
14 + y
## [1] 23  5

Running commands from a script

Open a new, blank script.

Type the following commands into the script file.

14 + 11

x = 11
14 + x

y = c(11, -11)
14 + y

Run a single line of code by placing the cursor anywhere on that line and clicking “Run” in the top right corner. (Note, however, if you highlight a portion of a line, it will only run the highlighted bit.)

Run multiple lines by highlighting and clicking “Run.”

The crasch package

Note that R is a case sensitive language, so type exactly as shown (OR use copy/paste OR open the script file provided on bCourses.)

Installing crasch

# This first package allows you to install from github
install.packages("devtools")
library(devtools)

# Now, install crasch
install_github("amyarneson/crasch")
# This may take a few minutes; multiple packages will be installed
# You may see some warning messages, and that's okay!
# You only need to install the package once...
  # ...unless you are instructed to update/re-install by Yukie or 
  # Amy in the future!

Loading the crasch package

library(crasch)
## Loading required package: WrightMap
## Warning: package 'WrightMap' was built under R version 3.2.4
## Loading required package: RColorBrewer
# This "opens" the crasch package within your R session
# You will need to run the library() command each time you open R
# A few messages and warnings are expected

Setting your working directory

crasch will save output to any folder on your computer, but you must tell it which folder!

  • Click the ‘Files’ tab of the bottom right window in RStudio.
  • Click the ‘…’ button located on the right side.
  • Navigate to your chosen folder and open it.
  • Click the ‘More’ button and choose ‘Set as working directory.’

Alternately, you can set your working directory with the function setwd() if you know the complete path to that folder. Be sure to include quotation marks!

setwd("/Users/Amy/Desktop/project")   # OSX
setwd("C:/Users/Amy/Desktop/project") # Windows

Running a crasch analysis

Run a test analysis using data that is provided with the package install. This data is called SUP because it represents the level of support of teachers regarding the adoption of a school-wide writing rubric. (This data is from Amy’s class project.)

# It is important to store the results in an R object
tutorial1 = craschR(SUPwide, itemInfo = SUPitem, consInfo = SUPcons, 
                    estPackage = "TAM", writeout = TRUE)
  • tutorial1 is the object that stores all of the estimation information
  • craschR() is the function
  • everything inside the parentheses are called arguments to the function

You can name objects as you wish using alphanumeric characters (A-Z, a-z, 0-9), underscores, and periods. Some things to note:

  • it must start with a letter,
  • if you re-use a name, it will overwrite whatever is currently loaded in the environment, and
  • these objects are saved to working memory which means they cannot be accessed again once you end your R session unless you explicitly save them.

Viewing ouput

Because we used writeout = TRUE, new files that contain the results of your analysis should now be in your working directory.

These are saved as CSVs and can be viewed using Excel or your favorite spreadsheet program.

You can also view the results in R.

names(tutorial1)
##  [1] "itemPars"       "itemSEs"        "itemThres"      "itemFit"       
##  [5] "persPars"       "persSEs"        "persRaw"        "persMax"

## [17] "itemInfo"       "consInfo"       "varsInfo"

Creating and viewing plots/graphs

You will likely use plots to display your analysis results.

wm(tutorial1)

The Wright Map should show in the Plots tab. Click the Zoom button to open it in a larger window.

Saving plots/graphs

You can save the plot as an image using the RStudio menus within the Plots tab.

Alternatively, use writeout = TRUE and specify an file type and it will be written to your working directory. You can then include the image in presentation slides or other documents.

wm(tutorial1, writeout = TRUE, imageType = "png")

Accessing documentation / help files

You can view documentation in RStudio using “?”

?crasch
?craschR
